We're going to be done.

00:45:50.130 --> 00:45:52.210
We've got about ten minutes.

00:45:52.210 --> 00:45:53.590
Do you have a question or two?

00:45:53.590 --> 00:46:00.940
Something you want to ask me?

00:46:00.940 --> 00:46:03.780
[ Laughter ]

00:46:03.780 --> 00:46:06.460
Nobody? Hello?

00:46:06.460 --> 00:46:07.760
Uh, hello?

00:46:07.760 --> 00:46:09.230
Hi! Hey!

00:46:09.230 --> 00:46:11.200
&gt;&gt; Geez, that's loud!

00:46:11.200 --> 00:46:15.280
Crazy! Anyway, I was just
wondering if you have any plans to,

00:46:15.280 --> 00:46:17.680
or can tell us a progress report

00:46:17.680 --> 00:46:22.140
on the third Jack Sawyer
novel with Peter Straub?

00:46:22.140 --> 00:46:25.500
&gt;&gt; Stephen King: Yeah, Peter and I
wrote a book called The Talisman.

00:46:25.500 --> 00:46:31.300
Then we wrote another one called
Black House, and with any luck,

00:46:31.300 --> 00:46:34.410
we will start the third
one in February next year.

00:46:34.410 --> 00:46:37.310
[ Applause ]

00:46:37.310 --> 00:46:41.470
We know just what it's
supposed to be, so.

00:46:41.470 --> 00:46:43.310
Anything else?

00:46:43.310 --> 00:46:47.420 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Being from New Jersey, and
you're a huge Bruce Springsteen fan,

00:46:47.420 --> 00:46:49.820
what's your favorite
Bruce Springsteen song?

00:46:51.480 --> 00:46:55.370
&gt;&gt; Stephen King: That's crazy,
that's like asking you know,

00:46:55.370 --> 00:46:57.340
what's the best movie
that you ever saw?

00:46:57.340 --> 00:47:02.000
There are so many Bruce Springsteen
songs that I like, that I love.

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:07.090
I guess maybe Rosalita,
Come Out Tonight.

00:47:07.090 --> 00:47:09.350
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:47:09.350 --> 00:47:16.410
&gt;&gt; We were going down to
Florida with my teenage son.

00:47:16.410 --> 00:47:19.460
And of course, didn't have
devices then and so on.

00:47:19.460 --> 00:47:21.470
And he said, "Well,
how about a book?

00:47:21.470 --> 00:47:22.990
I've got some Stephen King books?"

00:47:22.990 --> 00:47:25.130
And he said, "No, I don't
think I want to read that."

00:47:25.130 --> 00:47:26.440
&gt;&gt; Stephen King: Yeah, you
don't want to read that.

00:47:26.440 --> 00:47:29.290
&gt;&gt; So what I gave him, I
gave him the Bachman Books,

00:47:29.290 --> 00:47:32.370
and it was like a gateway
drug to your books.

00:47:32.370 --> 00:47:33.670
[ Laughter ]

00:47:33.670 --> 00:47:36.420
&gt;&gt; Stephen King: That's the first
time anybody ever called me a

00:47:36.420 --> 00:47:37.740
gateway drug!

00:47:37.740 --> 00:47:42.340
&gt;&gt; So I just wanted to ask the
background, why you used that --

00:47:42.340 --> 00:47:44.230
&gt;&gt; Stephen King: He started
out on Bachman and then he was

00:47:44.230 --> 00:47:46.170
on heroin of Stephen King.

00:47:46.170 --> 00:47:47.470
[ Applause ]

00:47:47.470 --> 00:47:51.620
&gt;&gt; No, I just wondered if you
could give me a little background

00:47:51.620 --> 00:47:54.290
on why you decided to
do the Bachman Books.

00:47:54.290 --> 00:47:58.630
&gt;&gt; Stephen King: Well, the
thing was there was a time

00:47:58.630 --> 00:48:02.440
when publishers thought that if you
published more than one book a year

00:48:02.440 --> 00:48:06.150
or possibly every 18 months,
you were overpublishing.

00:48:06.150 --> 00:48:08.070
And I had this period that I went

00:48:08.070 --> 00:48:09.910
through that was extremely
productive,

00:48:09.910 --> 00:48:14.190
and this stuff just
poured out of me.

00:48:14.190 --> 00:48:20.460
The new stuff that was being
published year by year, Carrie,

00:48:20.460 --> 00:48:24.530
Salem's Lot, The Shining, The
Stand, Nightshift, and all that.

00:48:24.530 --> 00:48:26.320
But I had these other books,

00:48:26.320 --> 00:48:29.270
some of which had been
written on my teenage years.

00:48:29.270 --> 00:48:31.940
They all weren't good.

00:48:31.940 --> 00:48:37.680
And some never should see the
light of day and never will.

00:48:37.680 --> 00:48:40.210
But there were a couple
like Long Walk and --

00:48:40.210 --> 00:48:41.510
[ Applause ]

00:48:41.510 --> 00:48:47.340
Road Work that I thought
were pretty good.

00:48:47.340 --> 00:48:51.690
So they got, they were
published as paperback originals.

00:48:51.690 --> 00:48:55.990
And the original name that I
decided to publish those books

00:48:55.990 --> 00:48:59.590
under was my grandfather's
name, Guy Pillsbury.

00:48:59.590 --> 00:49:04.140
And I got a panic call
from the editor two

00:49:04.140 --> 00:49:07.800
or three days before the books
went to press and said, "Oh,

00:49:07.800 --> 00:49:11.100
the copyright got out,
and it's under your name.

00:49:11.100 --> 00:49:15.830
And people will find out this
is -- that Guy Pillsbury is you.

00:49:15.830 --> 00:49:18.830
So you need another name,
and you need it right away."

00:49:18.830 --> 00:49:24.950
And I was reading a paperback
novel by Richard Stark,

00:49:24.950 --> 00:49:28.390
and Bachman Turner
Overdrive was on the stereo.

00:49:28.390 --> 00:49:32.010
So I said, "Call me Richard
Bachman," and that's what happened.

00:49:32.010 --> 00:49:39.140
[ Applause ]

00:49:39.140 --> 00:49:42.600
&gt;&gt; Do you read books
once or over and over?

00:49:42.600 --> 00:49:47.360
&gt;&gt; Stephen King: I read
very few over and over.

00:49:47.360 --> 00:49:50.630
There are books like
Lord of the Flies.

00:49:50.630 --> 00:49:57.990
There's a wonderful novel by Thomas
Williams called Whipple's Castle.

00:49:57.990 --> 00:50:05.690
The Hannibal Lecter
Trilogy by Thomas Harris.

00:50:06.790 --> 00:50:09.790
Those books I've read
over and over again.

00:50:09.790 --> 00:50:14.870
But there are so many books that
I have more of a tendency to --

00:50:14.870 --> 00:50:19.550
you know, like anybody else,
I have favorite writers that I

00:50:19.550 --> 00:50:23.440
like that I have a tendency
to go back to again and again.

00:50:23.440 --> 00:50:25.020
People like John Sanford.

00:50:25.020 --> 00:50:28.850
I never miss a John Sanford book.

00:50:28.850 --> 00:50:37.010 position:56%
There's a writer, Dutch writer named
Herman Koch that I really enjoy.

00:50:37.010 --> 00:50:39.000
Of course, like everybody
else in the world,

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:42.170
I read those books
about Lisbeth Salander.

00:50:42.170 --> 00:50:45.920
I didn't think the guy
was much of a writer,

00:50:45.920 --> 00:50:47.620
but geez, could he ever narrate!

00:50:47.620 --> 00:50:48.920
So I like those.

00:50:48.920 --> 00:50:56.080
So I have a tendency to move along
because you only get so many books.

00:50:56.080 --> 00:50:59.860
I'm haunted sometimes by the
thought of all the great books

00:50:59.860 --> 00:51:03.160
that I've missed somewhere
along the line.

00:51:03.160 --> 00:51:07.380
But it's like having misplaced
socks, but only worse.

00:51:07.380 --> 00:51:09.050
Something else?

00:51:09.050 --> 00:51:13.060
I'm going as fast as I
can because they're going

00:51:13.060 --> 00:51:15.930
to kick us all out of here.

00:51:15.930 --> 00:51:17.520
&gt;&gt; I didn't have a single question.

00:51:17.520 --> 00:51:30.690
I just wanted you to stand still so
I could get an unfettered picture.

00:51:30.690 --> 00:51:31.990
[ Cheers ]

00:51:31.990 --> 00:51:33.290
&gt;&gt; Stephen King: Standing
still is foreign to my nature.

00:51:33.290 --> 00:51:36.590
And listen, you know, being up
here scares the [bleep] out of me!

00:51:36.590 --> 00:51:38.700 position:56%
Okay? That's a lot of lot of people.

00:51:38.700 --> 00:51:42.510
I'm a guy who does my best
work in a room all by myself.

00:51:42.510 --> 00:51:46.530
Of course I'm also a guy
who does his best work

00:51:46.530 --> 00:51:47.950
in a room with somebody else.

00:51:47.950 --> 00:51:51.280
But -- ah.

00:51:51.280 --> 00:51:56.540
I'm just -- all I'm doing is
stylin' a little bit wit cha.

00:51:56.540 --> 00:51:57.840
That's it.

00:51:57.840 --> 00:52:03.000
Let's do, like two more quickies,
and then you can all go get lunch.

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:04.900
We'll break for lunch.

00:52:04.900 --> 00:52:06.200
Anything?

00:52:06.200 --> 00:52:07.500
&gt;&gt; Hi, Mr. King.

00:52:07.500 --> 00:52:08.800
&gt;&gt; Stephen King: Hi.

00:52:08.800 --> 00:52:10.360
&gt;&gt; I just want to say
first as a writer,

00:52:10.360 --> 00:52:16.230
you've been a great inspiration,
so thank you very much.

00:52:16.230 --> 00:52:17.530
&gt;&gt; Stephen King: You're
welcome, thank you.

00:52:17.530 --> 00:52:20.790
&gt;&gt; I was just wondering,
what scares you?

00:52:20.790 --> 00:52:24.480
[ Laughter ]

00:52:24.480 --> 00:52:25.780 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Stephen King: I'm looking at him.

00:52:25.780 --> 00:52:27.080
I mean.

00:52:27.080 --> 00:52:28.380
[ Laughter ]

00:52:28.380 --> 00:52:30.940
I mean, the little things
like, there are little things

00:52:30.940 --> 00:52:36.300
like you say, "Okay, I'm standing
in front of 1000, 2000 people.

00:52:36.300 --> 00:52:39.710
Did I zip my fly before
I came out here?"

00:52:39.710 --> 00:52:42.490
And you know, to be
absolutely dead serious,

00:52:42.490 --> 00:52:46.450
I'm scared to death of
Alzheimer's Disease.

00:52:46.450 --> 00:52:55.030 position:56%
Senility. I live by my wits, and
I'm afraid of my wits slipping away.

00:52:55.030 --> 00:53:02.500
Otherwise, I'm afraid of -- geez,
I guess just about everything!

00:53:03.690 --> 00:53:06.490
Spiders are a great
big no-no with me.

00:53:06.490 --> 00:53:08.720
I hate the idea of
spiders, and of course a lot

00:53:08.720 --> 00:53:14.330
of this stuff was inculcated
in me at a very young age.

00:53:14.330 --> 00:53:20.660
My mother started us off on
Bambi, and then moved directly

00:53:20.660 --> 00:53:23.430
onto Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde.

00:53:24.500 --> 00:53:27.360
And one of her favorite
stories was she talked about --

00:53:27.360 --> 00:53:30.510
she was one of, I think,
eight or nine kids.

00:53:30.510 --> 00:53:31.830
Grew up in Scarborough, Maine.

00:53:31.830 --> 00:53:34.160
This was around the
turn of the century.

00:53:34.160 --> 00:53:39.330
And once a week a guy came
along, and he would trade stuff.

00:53:39.330 --> 00:53:42.120
And he had gum for the kids.

00:53:42.120 --> 00:53:45.780
And you had to chew that
piece of gum all week.

00:53:45.780 --> 00:53:47.710
So my mother had this gum.

00:53:47.710 --> 00:53:51.650
You know, you chew it and put
it on the bedpost at night.

00:53:51.650 --> 00:53:56.480 position:56%
And it would harden up, and the next
morning you'd have to pop it in,

00:53:56.480 --> 00:53:59.230
soften it up so it was
good to go for another day.

00:53:59.230 --> 00:54:02.750
And one night after my mother
put her gum on the bedpost,

00:54:02.750 --> 00:54:06.160
a moth came down and
lit on it and got stuck.

00:54:06.160 --> 00:54:09.600
And when she woke up the next
morning, she didn't look.

00:54:09.600 --> 00:54:12.610
She just popped her
gum into her mouth.

00:54:12.610 --> 00:54:14.810
She said she bit it in half,

00:54:14.810 --> 00:54:19.240
and the two halves were
fluttering inside her mouth.

00:54:19.240 --> 00:54:23.230
And I thought to myself, "Mom, at
some point I'm going to use that."

00:54:23.230 --> 00:54:24.530
[ Laughter ]

00:54:24.530 --> 00:54:26.380
And that's just what I did.

00:54:26.380 --> 00:54:27.680
One more.

00:54:27.680 --> 00:54:29.730
&gt;&gt; Alright, thank you
very much real quick.

00:54:29.730 --> 00:54:33.550
Dark Tower is my favorite
book series of all time.

00:54:33.550 --> 00:54:34.850
[ Cheers ]

00:54:34.850 --> 00:54:38.080
So I'm curious, as an author
that's had so many movies written

00:54:38.080 --> 00:54:41.570
from their books, how nervous or
worried do you get when someone

00:54:41.570 --> 00:54:43.870
like Roland, who you've
spent so much time with,

00:54:43.870 --> 00:54:46.240
is going to be put
up on the big screen?

00:54:46.240 --> 00:54:47.540
&gt;&gt; Stephen King: Well,
I'm more nervous

00:54:47.540 --> 00:54:50.230
about this than I am most of them.

00:54:50.230 --> 00:54:58.020 position:56%
In most cases, my feeling is if
somebody buys a book to make a movie

00:54:58.020 --> 00:55:02.850
out of or a TV series, it's like
sending a kid off to college, okay?

00:55:02.850 --> 00:55:06.060 position:56%
You hope that they're going to do a
good job, and that they're not going

00:55:06.060 --> 00:55:08.290
to get into trouble, and
they're not go to get expelled

00:55:08.290 --> 00:55:12.380
and they're not going to be
arrested or anything like that.

00:55:12.380 --> 00:55:15.620
But every now and then,
that happens.

00:55:15.620 --> 00:55:17.050
You just hope for the best.

00:55:17.050 --> 00:55:22.850
And man, I've had terrific luck,
you know, between Shawshank,

00:55:22.850 --> 00:55:25.300
which I really did
write, by the way.

00:55:25.300 --> 00:55:28.360
And the Green Mile and
Misery and Stand by Me.

00:55:28.360 --> 00:55:31.700
There have been a bunch
of stuff -- thank you.

00:55:31.700 --> 00:55:36.820
But remember, I didn't
write those movies.

00:55:36.820 --> 00:55:38.880
I just wrote the source,
although I think a lot

00:55:38.880 --> 00:55:40.660
of times the movies are better.

00:55:40.660 --> 00:55:43.140
This is just my personal opinion.

00:55:43.140 --> 00:55:45.360
But when they stick
closer to the source,

00:55:45.360 --> 00:55:47.420
they tend to be a little better.

00:55:47.420 --> 00:55:55.940
But the fans of The Dark
Tower are so, so loyal, so --

00:55:55.940 --> 00:55:59.270
I started to say rabid, but
that was the wrong word.

00:55:59.270 --> 00:56:02.140
Made me think of Cujo.

00:56:02.140 --> 00:56:06.990
But they care about those books,
so I want the movies to be good.

00:56:06.990 --> 00:56:09.550
I'm a little bit nervous about it.

00:56:09.550 --> 00:56:13.600
But you know, it's a thrill.

00:56:13.600 --> 00:56:14.900
It's going to be a thrill.

00:56:14.900 --> 00:56:17.540
I've seen some of the
dailies and some of the rushes

00:56:17.540 --> 00:56:19.450
from the movie, and it looks right.

00:56:19.450 --> 00:56:22.150
So I've got my fingers crossed.

00:56:22.150 --> 00:56:23.660
Listen, you guys have
been great to me.

00:56:23.660 --> 00:56:24.960
Thank you so much!

00:56:24.960 --> 00:56:26.260
[ Applause ]

00:56:26.260 --> 00:56:28.560
Thank you.

